<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,466,1010,1069]" box="[151,302,1045,1069]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,294,1045,1069]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Figs. 90–97</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1119,1927]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[151,373,1120,1144]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body bicoloured, head to thorax yellow to brownish yellow, abdominal segments yellow or brownish yellow with median half of tergites II to VIII (
<figureCitation box="[817,902,1157,1181]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
) and segments IX to X dark brown; antennal segments I to III yellow, IV to VII dark brown often with basal third to half pale; fore wings brown with basal fifth including clavus slightly pale; all legs yellow; prominent body setae dark brown. Head (
<figureCitation box="[1132,1213,1231,1255]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 90</figureCitation>
) rounded at cheeks. Ocellar setae III just lateral to fore ocellus. Postocular setae I the longest and much longer than longitudinal diameter of hind ocelli, II and IV minute. Antennae (
<figureCitation box="[744,825,1306,1330]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
) 7-segmented. Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1123,1205,1306,1330]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 90</figureCitation>
) strongly sculptured with transverse striae, with about 40 discal setae; posteroangular setae 2 pairs; posteromarginal setae 3 pairs. Metascutum (
<figureCitation box="[310,397,1381,1405]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
) sculptured with longitudinal striae except anteromedially; median pair of setae behind anterior margin; CPS present. Fore wing first vein with seven basal and three distal setae. Abdominal tergites with small scallops along posterior margin, these scallops distinct on posterior segments; tergite II with 4 lateral marginal setae; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[469,550,1493,1517]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
) with posteromarginal comb complete, microtrichia often irregular in length or space; tergite IX with two pairs of CPS; sternite I without microsetae anteromedially; sternites III to VII (
<figureCitation box="[1345,1427,1530,1554]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 95</figureCitation>
) with about 14 (II with 3 or 4) discal setae transversely arranged in nearly straight line; sternite VII with S1 setae far from posterior margin; pleurotergites without discal setae and ciliate microtrichia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1119,1927]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[199,394,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Male macroptera</emphasis>
. Body uniformly pale yellow. Antennal segment VI with more 20 setae. Abdominal tergite VIII without posteromarginal comb; tergite IX (
<figureCitation box="[689,770,1679,1703]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 96</figureCitation>
) with S1 setae at level of S2 setae and slightly shorter than S2 setae, their bases equidistant; sternites III to VII (
<figureCitation box="[739,820,1717,1741]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–103" captionStartId="29.[151,263,1782,1805]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,203,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-103@29.[151,1436,193,1761]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 90–103. Thrips species. T. coloratus, female 90–95: (90) Head &amp; pronotum; (91) Antenna, left; (92) Metascutum; (93) Tergite VI, left side, median part between two longitudinal dot lines is dark area; (94) Tergites VIII–X; (95) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. coloratus, male 96–97: (96) Tergite IX; (97) Sternite VI, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, female 98– 101: (98) Head &amp; pronotum; (99) Antenna, right; (100) Metascutum; (101) Sternite V, sculpture omitted. T. extensicornis, male 102–103: (102) Tergite IX; (103) Sternite V." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
) each with an oblong pore plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1119,1927]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,1754,1779]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Comments</emphasis>
. This species is distributed throughout 
<collectingCountry box="[779,847,1755,1778]" name="Japan" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Japan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[858,941,1754,1778]" name="Taiwan" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[977,1036,1754,1778]" name="India" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1091,1200,1754,1778]" name="Australia" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Australia</collectingCountry>
. It is one of the most common flower-living species in 
<collectingCountry box="[555,624,1792,1815]" name="Japan" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Japan</collectingCountry>
. Female adults of 
<taxonomicName box="[853,961,1792,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coloratus">
<emphasis box="[853,961,1792,1816]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">coloratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished easily from other species by the body colour. The population on Ogasawara Islands has been considered to be same species although their body is uniformly dark brown in both sexes (
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer, J. M." box="[851,1010,1866,1890]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 76" refId="ref54112" refString="Palmer, J. M. (1992) Thrips (Thysanoptera) from Pakistan to the Pacific: a review. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology, 61 (1), 1 - 76." type="journal article" year="1992">Palmer, 1992</bibRefCitation>
), but this is here described as a new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
